2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.06273221-e7a9-40ed-84c1-22de3907176a.description=
Runs the requested SQL Command, returns the number of row(s) affected and any lateral effect.

Inputs\:
host	- Hostname or IP address of the SQL Server.
username	- The username of the SQL or Windows user credentials to login to the SQL Server.  If use Windows authentication, username input should be in the format like\: domain\username. 
password	- Password of the user account.
instance        - The named instance of SQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
dbPort	- The port on which the SQL Server database service is listening on.
database 	- The name of the database to run the command on.
authType	- Whether Windows authentication or SQL authentication should be used. Default is SQL.
command 	- The actual SQL command to run (either T-SQL, Stored Procedure, or Extended procedure).
timeout 	- Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. It defaults to 30 seconds.

Result\:
The number of rows affected.

Extra results\:
outputText -	 Output result for the command (if this is the case).

Responses\:
success 	- The command was successful.
failure 	- There was a problem running the command.

Notes\:
1. When informational commands (like dbcc) are run through the command, end the command with "with tableresults" in order to populate the outputText output with the obtained result.
2. Use the Sql Query operation instead of Sql Command when Select queries are to be run.
3. Please refer to the Notes in the Microsoft SQL folder description for the general integration information of Microsoft SQL Server.
2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.16055595-5fdd-48b1-a3e2-74bd8440bf8a.description=Retrieves a system account username and password and stores the values as flow variables. Inputs\: accountName - The name of the system account. Starting with OO Platform version 10.20, the relative path of the system account can also be used. flowVariable - The flow variables prefix to store the system account into. The operation will receive one input with the flow variable name to assign to, but will actually assign the account to two separate variables. So if the input flowVar was "sysAcct" then two flow vars will be created "sysAcctUsername" and "sysAcctPassword". Results\: Result - A message indicating if the operation was successful or not. Responses\: success - The operation completed as stated in the description. failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. 2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.2d795cd1-d9b9-4c56-9038-dbb8a5b9b9ea.description=
This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.2e9d2a57-dd9f-4076-a0ed-f75a9f2fded2.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.5e3179e9-a00c-4ef0-9f2f-d431e73b0b07.description=
Checks if a number or word is less than or equal to another number or word. Word comparison is case-sensitive in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
value1 <\= value2

Responses\:
success - The boolean operation was evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.
2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.6a0fc930-cc20-4837-8770-6a066dfba4ca.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Gets a list of one or more Elements in a list that match to the value specified in the input "compareTo" based on the input "matchType".  

Inputs\:
list - The list to search.
delimiter - The delimiter that separates elements in list.
compareTo - The string to compare each element in the list against.
matchType - The type of match to perform.

Responses\:
success - 1 or more elements were found that matched.
failure - no elements matched, or something went wrong.

Results\:
others -  A delimiter delimited list of elements that do not match
matches - A delimiter delimited list of elements that match the rule.

2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.d65ccefb-f655-42dd-a712-03b9053e945f.description=
This step will insert the ddr records into automation db

Inputs\:
    host - Hostname or IP address of the SQL Server.
    username	- The username of the SQL or Windows user credentials to login to the SQL Server.  If use Windows authentication, username input should be in the format like\: domain\username. 
    password	- Password of the user account.
    instance - The named instance of SQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
    dbPort - The port on which the SQL Server database service is listening on.
Default value\: 1433
    database - The name of the database to run the command on.
    authType	- Whether Windows authentication or SQL authentication should be used. 
Valid values\: sql, window
Default value\: sql
    query - The SQL query to run (either T-SQL, Stored Procedure, or Extended procedure).
    save - If true, saves the query execution result and database connection in session context.
Default value\: true
    delimiter - The delimiter to use between columns in returnResult and columnNames.
    keyName - The name of a key to help keep multiple query results distinct.
    multipleActiveResultSets - Allow multiple DataReaders open concurrently on the same connection.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL query execution.
Default value\: 30

Results\:
   ddrRecords
   insertDBFailFlag
  errorMessages

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - Failed to execute the query.

Notes\: 
1. Refer to the Notes in the Microsoft SQL folder description. 
2. This operation runs SQL SELECT statement. To run SQL command  (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE), use the 'SQL Command' or 'SQL Script' operation.
3. To get the query result, set the value of the  input to 'true'.
4. The database connection will close automatically after the query has executed if you set the value of the  input to 'false', or of the operation returns a 'failure' or 'no more items' response.
5. 'SQL Query' is an iterative operation, so while the operation's response is 'more items', the database connection stays open. It closes when the response is 'no more items'. If you want to exit the loop before reaching the 'no more items' response, close the database connection using the 'Close Database Connection' operation. For the deprecated 'SQL Query (1)' and 'Get Next Sql Row' operations, the database connection stays open while 'Get Next Sql Row' responds 'has more rows'. It closes when the response is 'no more rows'. If you want to exit the loop before reaching the 'no more rows' response, close the database connection using the 'Close Database Connection' operation.
6. If the 'SQL Query' operation is used with different query commands in different steps in a flow, specify a different key value in each step to guarantee the uniqueness of the retrieve query results.

2b40f90f-1750-4b5b-be24-d25386b37ffb.ea46a5da-b93e-4602-bbef-16a081510eae.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
